spec: ab3196
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__, __lshift__, __rshift__ dict-presence for abc module types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, and type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) — the built-in function type."
    - "Key finding (__pow__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __pow__. abc.ABC is a plain abstract base class helper with no arithmetic semantics — ABC ** n is not a defined operation. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass responsible for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass registration (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__); none of these capabilities map to exponentiation. The function type (type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>) does not define __pow__ — functions are callables, not numeric types. f ** n is not a valid Python expression."
    - "Key finding (__lshift__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __lshift__. Left-shift is a bitwise integer operator with no role in abc's abstract class machinery. abc.ABCMeta does not define << for class hierarchy operations; its class registration protocol is entirely method-based (register(), __subclasshook__). abc.ABC has no operator overloads whatsoever — it is a bare metaclass convenience wrapper. The function type does not define __lshift__ — f << n is not a valid Python expression; there is no left-shift semantics for callable objects."
    - "Key finding (__rshift__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __rshift__. Right-shift is also absent from all abc types. abc.abstractmethod is a decorator implemented as a function; type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>, which has no __rshift__. abc.ABCMeta continues its all-false streak across arithmetic and bitwise operators — its power lies exclusively in class-hierarchy machinery. abc.ABC defines no operators of any kind."
    - "All 9 values in this wave are false — continuing the all-false pattern from wave 659 (__truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__)."
    - "The function type profile across all waves: true only for __get__ (wave 652), __repr__ (wave 655), and __call__ (wave 656). All other dunders tested — including this wave's __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — are false."
    - "abc.ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic and bitwise dunder tested across 9 consecutive waves (652–660). Its entire capability is expressed through class-hierarchy machinery, not operator overloading."
    - "Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false."
    - "  Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false."
    - "  Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false."
    - "  Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __pow__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__pow__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __pow__.
# abc.ABC: a plain abstract base class helper; not an arithmetic type.
#   ABC ** n or ABC ** ABC is not defined — ABC is a class factory aid,
#   not a numeric or collection type. Its only purpose is to serve as a
#   convenient base class that has ABCMeta as its metaclass.
# abc.ABCMeta: a metaclass for abstract base class machinery; no ** operator.
#   ABCMeta handles class hierarchy, abstract method tracking, and virtual
#   subclass registration. None of these capabilities map to exponentiation.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __pow__. f ** n is not a valid Python
#   expression. Functions are callables, not numeric operands.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3196.pow:
  description: "abc types __pow__ dict-presence checks; wave 660"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3196

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3196001", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__pow__"], false]
    - ["ab3196002", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__pow__"], false]
    - ["ab3196003", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__pow__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __lshift__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__lshift__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __lshift__.
# abc.ABC: no left-shift protocol; abstract base classes are not
#   integer types and do not participate in bitwise shift arithmetic.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define << for metaclass left-shift.
#   ABCMeta's power lies in __subclasshook__, register(), and
#   __abstractmethods__ — none of which involve bitwise operators.
#   ABCMeta class registration uses the register() method explicitly,
#   not a << shorthand.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __lshift__. f << n is not a valid Python
#   expression. Functions are not integer operands.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3196.lshift:
  description: "abc types __lshift__ dict-presence checks; wave 660"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3196

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3196004", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__lshift__"], false]
    - ["ab3196005", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__lshift__"], false]
    - ["ab3196006", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__lshift__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __rshift__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__rshift__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __rshift__.
# abc.ABC: no right-shift protocol; ABC is not an integer or bitwise type.
#   abc.ABC >> something is not a defined operation.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define >> for metaclass right-shift. ABCMeta is a
#   powerful metaclass, but its API surface (subclasshook, register,
#   abstractmethods) has no bitwise component. Right-shift on metaclass
#   objects is not a defined Python idiom.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __rshift__. f >> n is not a valid Python
#   expression. The function type is scoped to its role as a callable,
#   displayable, descriptor — no bitwise operators are defined.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3196.rshift:
  description: "abc types __rshift__ dict-presence checks; wave 660"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3196

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3196007", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__rshift__"], false]
    - ["ab3196008", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__rshift__"], false]
    - ["ab3196009", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__rshift__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __pow__, __lshift__, __rshift__ across all 3 abc subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 3 classes x 3 methods = 9 rows.
# __pow__:    false for all 3.
# __lshift__: false for all 3.
# __rshift__: false for all 3.
# All 9 values are false.
# Continues the all-false pattern from wave 659 (__truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__).
# The function type profile across all waves tested:
#   true:  __get__ (652), __repr__ (655), __call__ (656)
#   false: __set__, __delete__, __hash__, __eq__, __bool__, __lt__, __le__, __gt__,
#          __ge__, __str__, __len__, __getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__,
#          __contains__, __add__, __sub__, __mul__, __truediv__, __floordiv__,
#          __mod__, __pow__, __lshift__, __rshift__
# The function type is tightly scoped to its role as a callable descriptor with
#   a display representation. All arithmetic and bitwise operators are absent.
# abc.ABCMeta note: ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic and
#   bitwise dunder tested across 9 consecutive waves (652–660). Its power lies
#   exclusively in class-hierarchy machinery — not in operator overloading.
# abc.ABC note: ABC is a pure syntactic convenience for declaring abstract base
#   classes. It has no state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides, and defines
#   no arithmetic, bitwise, or collection protocol whatsoever.
# Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:
#   Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false.
#   Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false.
#   Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false.
#   Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

